WEBVTT

00:05.730 --> 00:08.573
Welcome to the podcast for Pretty Survey Methodist Church.

00:09.314 --> 00:14.479
My name is Dudley and today is Thursday, February 26th.

00:16.201 --> 00:21.186
Our reading is from Matthew 21, verses one through 22.

00:21.486 --> 00:27.912
And today we wanna talk about a couple of different things.

00:29.174 --> 00:33.458
We wanna talk about a donkey and we wanna talk about

00:34.530 --> 00:35.731
No word, Hosanna.

00:36.572 --> 00:47.983
Growing up on a farm, I've been around donkeys quite a bit, and I have a memory that's ingrained in my mind.

00:48.003 --> 01:04.178
I would be riding around with my grandfather in the farm truck, windows down, arms hanging out, and we'd pull over, and he would see his donkey out there, and he'd yell out, Hey Jack!

01:05.346 --> 01:11.796
And man, that donkey would go to sing, and he would he-haul, he-haul.

01:13.038 --> 01:14.139
Just a funny time.

01:14.840 --> 01:18.165
I guess he thought it was supper time, and he was really excited about it.

01:19.227 --> 01:21.551
But what is it about a donkey in today's reading?

01:22.852 --> 01:30.724
Donkeys don't seem very majestic, and yet Jesus chooses to ride into town on a donkey.

01:32.427 --> 01:34.450
And this cry of Hosanna, what is it?

01:34.562 --> 01:38.406
It has to be more than something that you yell at a parade.

01:39.887 --> 01:48.936
Jesus was fulfilling prophecy, one that said, see your king comes to you gentle and riding on a donkey.

01:51.559 --> 01:55.542
In Bible times, the donkey could be seen as an indicator of wealth.

01:56.523 --> 01:59.446
Job had around 500 donkeys.

01:59.486 --> 02:03.410
Abraham had many donkeys, and these were both rich men.

02:04.130 --> 02:11.141
And now we see that Jesus in our hearts, in our minds, we know that he truly owns everything.

02:11.822 --> 02:16.830
But when he came to earth, he was meek and lowly.

02:16.930 --> 02:17.631
He was humble.

02:18.072 --> 02:20.055
He wasn't rich in his earthly life.

02:21.698 --> 02:32.114
He even had to borrow a donkey to enter the city, to fulfill this prophecy, to fulfill the triumphant entry

02:33.922 --> 02:35.384
Here's another interesting point.

02:35.805 --> 02:38.910
When kings were going to war, they would ride a war horse.

02:40.052 --> 02:43.597
But in times of peace, kings would ride a donkey.

02:44.919 --> 02:51.369
So in today's reading, we see Jesus coming in peace, riding in on a donkey.

02:52.531 --> 02:55.836
Sure, he's the king of kings and he is all powerful.

02:57.058 --> 03:02.226
But he's also the prince of peace, making peace between God and man.

03:03.746 --> 03:33.042
Even though the people are under the heavy hand of the Roman Empire, Jesus is showing that he's the king, but that he has come to bring peace, not peace that this world sees, a peace that overthrows one government to set another one up, but he is king overall, and he has come to bring peace between God and man through salvation, through death and resurrection.

03:34.434 --> 03:39.041
The same crowd that is cheering him on right now will soon call for the crucifixion.

03:40.103 --> 03:43.348
They did not know the weight of what they were calling for.

03:44.289 --> 03:47.174
Soon they will be calling for him to be taken out through death.

03:48.035 --> 03:54.926
But through that calling and through that death, Jesus is going to provide salvation for those who believe.

03:56.067 --> 04:02.898
So as those who are unwittingly setting up Jesus' death, they are really making way

04:03.106 --> 04:06.532
for his power to shine through his salvation.

04:07.974 --> 04:18.371
Even those that are calling out for his crucifixion would have the opportunity to receive this salvation that Jesus is going to provide.

04:18.411 --> 04:23.920
Now that's true love, but they are not calling for that crucifixion just yet.

04:23.980 --> 04:29.810
As Jesus enters in the city, the crowd gathered is giving him honor.

04:29.954 --> 04:34.601
and giving him praise, they start yelling out this word, Hosanna.

04:35.663 --> 04:38.287
And Hosanna means save us, we pray.

04:39.709 --> 04:48.884
Well, they were probably talking about being saved from Rome's oppression, a political salvation, but that's not what Jesus is doing here.

04:49.585 --> 04:57.938
A political salvation is much too small, much too temporary, and it does not speak to our true need

04:58.114 --> 05:06.602
The deepest need that you and I have is salvation through the death, the burial and resurrection of Jesus Christ.

05:07.363 --> 05:14.409
The deepest need that we have is freedom from sin so that we can be in the presence of the Father for all of eternity.

05:15.951 --> 05:18.493
So as we close today, I want to encourage you.

05:18.533 --> 05:23.978
I want to remind you of a verse in the book of Jude, the very last part actually.

05:25.239 --> 05:28.082
Here is what the sacrifice of Jesus

05:28.226 --> 05:28.647
does.

05:29.468 --> 05:33.112
Here is the deliverance, the Hosanna, if you will.

05:34.614 --> 05:58.002
The scripture says to him who is able to keep you from stumbling and to present you before his glorious presence, without fault, and with great joy to the only God our Savior be glory, majesty, power, and authority through Jesus Christ, our Lord, before all ages, now and forevermore.

05:59.074 --> 05:59.555
Amen.

06:00.957 --> 06:06.464
Jesus, in his weakest moment, did the most powerful thing we could ever hope for.

06:07.185 --> 06:15.777
He came in humility and meekness and love, but was truly operating in unimaginable strength and ultimate victory.

06:16.919 --> 06:19.883
May you be blessed as you think upon these things.

06:21.405 --> 06:22.386
Have a blessed day.

